Expression of experimental uncertainties

example.p:
A high-quality Zener voltage standard is calibrated by comparison with a Josephson effect voltage reference based on the conventional value of the Josephson constant recommended for international use by the CIPM. The relative combined standard uncertainty
uc(VS)/VSu_{"c"}(ii(V)_{"S"})//ii(V)_{"S"}
uc(VS)/VSu_{"c"}(ii(V)_{"S"})//ii(V)_{"S"}
(see

[scls_5-1-6_ISO_JCGM_100_2008_EN_]
) of the calibrated potential difference
VSii(V)_{"S"}
VSii(V)_{"S"}
of the Zener standard is
2×10−82 xx 10^{-8}
2×10−82 xx 10^{-8}
when
VSii(V)_{"S"}
VSii(V)_{"S"}
is reported in terms of the conventional value, but
uc(VS)/VSu_{"c"}(ii(V)_{"S"})//ii(V)_{"S"}
uc(VS)/VSu_{"c"}(ii(V)_{"S"})//ii(V)_{"S"}
is
4×10−74 xx 10^{-7}
4×10−74 xx 10^{-7}
when
VSii(V)_{"S"}
VSii(V)_{"S"}
is reported in terms of the SI unit of potential difference, the volt (V), because of the additional uncertainty associated with the SI value of the Josephson constant.

li.p:
quantities whose values
and uncertainties
are directly determined in the current measurement. These values and uncertainties may be obtained from, for example, a single observation, repeated observations, or judgement based on experience, and may involve the determination of corrections to instrument readings and corrections for influence quantities, such as ambient temperature, barometric pressure, and humidity;
